    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n    <title>JavaScript Indexing Demonstration</title>\n    <style>\n        body {\n            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n            line-height: 1.6;\n            max-width: 800px;\n            margin: 0 auto;\n            padding: 20px;\n            background-color: #f5f5f5;\n        }\n        h1 {\n            color: #2c3e50;\n            border-bottom: 2px solid #3498db;\n            padding-bottom: 10px;\n        }\n        .section {\n            background-color: white;\n            padding: 15px;\n            margin: 15px 0;\n            border-radius: 5px;\n            box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);\n        }\n        button {\n            background-color: #3498db;\n            color: white;\n            border: none;\n            padding: 8px 15px;\n            border-radius: 4px;\n            cursor: pointer;\n            margin: 5px;\n        }\n        button:hover {\n            background-color: #2980b9;\n        }\n        pre {\n            background-color: #f8f9fa;\n            padding: 10px;\n            border-radius: 4px;\n            overflow-x: auto;\n        }\n        .output {\n            margin-top: 10px;\n            padding: 10px;\n            background-color: #e8f4f8;\n            border-radius: 4px;\n        }\n    </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n    <h1>JavaScript Indexing Concepts</h1>\n    \n    <div class=\"section\">\n        <h2>Array Indexing</h2>\n        <p>Arrays use zero-based indexing in JavaScript (first element is at index 0).</p>\n        <pre>const fruits = ['Apple', 'Banana', 'Cherry', 'Date'];</pre>\n        <button onclick=\"demoArrayIndexing()\">Demonstrate Array Indexing</button>\n        <div id=\"arrayOutput\" class=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n    \n    <div class=\"section\">\n        <h2>String Indexing</h2>\n        <p>Strings can also be accessed by index like arrays (read-only).</p>\n        <pre>const message = 'Hello World';</pre>\n        <button onclick=\"demoStringIndexing()\">Demonstrate String Indexing</button>\n        <div id=\"stringOutput\" class=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n    \n    <div class=\"section\">\n        <h2>Object Property Indexing</h2>\n        <p>Object properties can be accessed using dot notation or bracket notation (like indexing).</p>\n        <pre>const user = {\n    name: 'Alice',\n    age: 30,\n    email: 'alice@example.com'\n};</pre>\n        <button onclick=\"demoObjectIndexing()\">Demonstrate Object Indexing</button>\n        <div id=\"objectOutput\" class=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n    \n    <div class=\"section\">\n        <h2>Finding Index Positions</h2>\n        <p>Finding the index of an element in an array.</p>\n        <pre>const colors = ['Red', 'Green', 'Blue', 'Green', 'Yellow'];</pre>\n        <button onclick=\"demoFindingIndex()\">Find Index of 'Blue'</button>\n        <button onclick=\"demoLastIndex()\">Find Last Index of 'Green'</button>\n        <div id=\"findIndexOutput\" class=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n    \n    <script>\n        // Array Indexing\n        function demoArrayIndexing() {\n            const fruits = ['Apple', 'Banana', 'Cherry', 'Date'];\n            let output = `fruits[0]: ${fruits[0]}<br>`;\n            output += `fruits[2]: ${fruits[2]}<br>`;\n            output += `fruits.length: ${fruits.length}<br>`;\n            output += `Last element (fruits[fruits.length - 1]): ${fruits[fruits.length - 1]}`;\n            document.getElementById('arrayOutput').innerHTML = output;\n        }\n        \n        // String Indexing\n        function demoStringIndexing() {\n            const message = 'Hello World';\n            let output = `message[0]: ${message[0]}<br>`;\n            output += `message[6]: ${message[6]}<br>`;\n            output += `message.charAt(4): ${message.charAt(4)}<br>`;\n            output += `String length: ${message.length}`;\n            document.getElementById('stringOutput').innerHTML = output;\n        }\n        \n        // Object Indexing\n        function demoObjectIndexing() {\n            const user = {\n                name: 'Alice',\n                age: 30,\n                email: 'alice@example.com'\n            };\n            let output = `user.name: ${user.name}<br>`;\n            output += `user[\"age\"]: ${user[\"age\"]}<br>`;\n            \n            const prop = 'email';\n            output += `Using variable for index (user[prop]): ${user[prop]}`;\n            document.getElementById('objectOutput').innerHTML = output;\n        }\n        \n        // Finding Index Positions\n        function demoFindingIndex() {\n            const colors = ['Red', 'Green', 'Blue', 'Green', 'Yellow'];\n            const index = colors.indexOf('Blue');\n            document.getElementById('findIndexOutput').innerHTML = \n                `Index of 'Blue': ${index} (${index !== -1 ? 'Found' : 'Not found'})`;\n        }\n        \n        function demoLastIndex() {\n            const colors = ['Red', 'Green', 'Blue', 'Green', 'Yellow'];\n            const index = colors.lastIndexOf('Green');\n            document.getElementById('findIndexOutput').innerHTML = \n                `Last index of 'Green': ${index} (${index !== -1 ? 'Found' : 'Not found'})`;\n        }\n    </script>\n</body>\n</html>"
